    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "description",
      "value": "Design and execute a computational screening pipeline to test the hypothesis that oxygen vacancy formation energies in transition metal oxides (TMOs) differ systematically between pseudopotential (PP) and all-electron (AE) methods. The plan: (1) Select 3-4 representative TMOs (TiO₂, SrTiO₃, ZnO, CeO₂) covering different d-electron counts and vacancy chemistries. (2) For each, build a 2×2×2 supercell with a single O vacancy. (3) Run DFT calculations with both a PP code (VASP, PBE, 520 eV cutoff, PAW) and an AE code (FHI-aims, PBE, tight basis). (4) Compute vacancy formation energy E_vac = E(defect) - E(perfect) + ½ μ(O₂). (5) Compare ΔE_vac = E_vac(PP) - E_vac(AE) across systems. (6) Analyze charge density differences (Δρ = ρ(defect) - ρ(perfect)) to quantify charge redistribution differences between methods. (7) Perform Bader charge analysis on both PP and AE densities to track charge transfer to/from the vacancy site. (8) Report systematic bias, if any, and correlate with d-orbital occupancy."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "expected_prediction",
      "value": "For early TMOs (TiO₂, SrTiO₃), ΔE_vac ≈ +0.3–0.8 eV (PP predicts less stable vacancies, i.e., higher formation energy) because frozen-core PP underestimates charge transfer from TM d-orbitals to the vacancy-localized states. For ZnO, ΔE_vac ≈ +0.1–0.3 eV (smaller effect due to filled d¹⁰ shell). For CeO₂, ΔE_vac ≈ +0.5–1.0 eV (largest effect due to strong f-orbital involvement in charge compensation). Bader charge analysis will show PP systematically underestimates electron depletion on TM atoms adjacent to the vacancy by ~0.1–0.3 e⁻ compared to AE."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "plan_id",
      "value": "plan_23c12a0a"
    }
  ],
